03612nam a22004813i 20180830145305.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||180827t20182018miua    ob    001 0 eng d  a9780472123643qelectronic book  z9780472037100qpaperbackqalkaline paper  z9780472130733qhardcover7 a10.3998/mpub.87735402doi  aMiUbengerdaepncMiU  aa-kr---aa------aa-ja---10aD810.C698bS66 20181 aSon, Elizabeth W.,eauthor.10aEmbodied reckonings :b"comfort women," performance, and transpacific redress /cElizabeth W. Son. 1aAnn Arbor, Michigan :bUniversity of Michigan Press,c[2018] 4c√2018  a1 online resource (xx, 267 pages) :billustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.0 aA Note on Transliteration and the Order of Names -- Prologue. Beginnings --Introduction. Reckoning with Histories of Violence and Erasure -- Embodying Claims for Redress: The Wednesday Demonstrations -- Staging Justice: The Women's International War Crimes Tribunal -- Redressive Theater: Histories of "Comfort Women" on the Stage -- Performances of Care: Memorial Building in the Korean Diaspora -- Epilogue. Until the End -- Notes -- Bibliography -- Index3 aEmbodied Reckonings examines the political and cultural aspects of contemporary performances that have grappled with the history of the "comfort women," the Japanese military's euphemism for the sexual enslavement of girls and young women-mostly Korean-in the years before and during World War II. Long silent, in the early 1990s these women and their supporters initiated varied performance practices-protests, tribunals, theater, and memorial-building projects-to demand justice for those affected by state-sponsored acts of violence. The book provides a critical framework for understanding how actions designed to bring about redress can move from the political and legal aspects of this concept to its cultural and social possibilities. Based on extensive archival and ethnographic research, the study argues for the central role of performance in how Korean survivors, activists, and artists have redressed the histories-and erasures-of this sexual violence. Merging cultural studies and performance theory with a transnational, feminist analysis, the book illuminates the actions of ordinary people, thus offering ways of reconceptualizing legal and political understandings of redress that tend to concentrate on institutionalized forms of state-based remediation.  aDescription based on information from publisher. 0aComfort womenzKorea. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocitieszAsia. 0aService, Compulsory non-militaryzJapan. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xWomenzKorea. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Korean. 0aReparations for historical injustices. 0aWomenxCrimes againstzKorea. 0aSexual abuse victimszKorea. 0aCollective memoryzKorea. 0aPerformance artxSocial aspectszKorea. 0aArtsxPolitical aspects. 0aFeminismzKorea. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)eissuing body.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.8773540